    <p>
      Junior nursing students start the semester with skill labs in the Old
      Jenkins Behavioral Science building where they work with mannequins and
      practice bedside care. The goal is to move to clinicals -- supervised
      sessions where students are able to work at a healthcare facility with
      real patients, before the end of the semester.
    </p>

    <p>
      When Morgan initially enrolled in a New York nursing school, she only
      stayed for one year. After her mother’s death, she decided to return to
      nursing and became a CNA. She was a single mother and didn’t want the same
      fate for her children.
    </p>

    <p>
      In her more than 26 years of nursing experience, Morgan’s noticed a
      difference in the way that Black nurses and White nurses are treated in
      the hospital.
    </p>

    <p>
      Morgan said it isn’t uncommon to see a White doctor completely ignore a
      Black nurse and instead, address a White nurse directly even though
      they’re both in the same room and have the same credentials.
    </p>

    <p>
      For that reason, she stresses the importance of education on her kids.
    </p>

    <p>
      “I always tell my kids, ‘you guys are African American, you got to finish
      school, you don’t want to suffer like I did,’” Morgan said.
    </p>

